  "@type": "SolutionRecord",
  "@id": "ocp:sep/epistemology-social",
  "meta": {
    "title": "Social Epistemology",
    "description": "Until recently, epistemology--the study of (the nature, sources, and pursuit of) knowledge--was heavily individualistic in focus. The emphasis was on the pursuit of knowledge by individual subjects, taken in isolation from their social environment. Social epistemology seeks to redress this imbalance by investigating the epistemic effects of social interactions, practices, norms, and systems. After briefly discussing the history of the field in sections 1 and 2, we move on to discuss central topics in social epistemology in section 3. Section 4 turns to recent approaches which use formal methods to characterize the functioning of epistemic communities like those in science. In section 5 we briefly turn to social epistemological approaches to the proper functioning of democratic societies, including responses to mis/disinformation as well as to the variety of epistemic dysfunctions that arise when we are in community with others.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T06:21:56.580Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T06:21:56.580Z",
    "datePublished": "2001-02-25T13:00:00.000Z",
